  "prompt": "How do you define a website with good usability, when everyone has different opinions on how things should behave?",
  "response": "Defining good website usability involves considering several key principles and best practices that generally improve user experience across different contexts:\n\n1. Universal Usability Principles\n- Clarity and simplicity\n- Intuitive navigation\n- Consistent design and interaction patterns\n- Fast loading times\n- Responsive and mobile-friendly design\n- Accessibility for users with disabilities\n\n2. User-Centered Design Elements\n- Clear, logical information hierarchy\n- Easily scannable content\n- Predictable page layouts\n- Minimal cognitive load\n- Prominent call-to-action buttons\n- Helpful error messages and guidance\n\n3. Technical Considerations\n- Cross-browser compatibility\n- Smooth performance\n- Clear typography\n- Appropriate color contrast\n- Efficient search functionality\n- Quick and straightforward forms\n\n4. User Research Methods\n- Conduct user testing\n- Create user personas\n- Perform A/B testing\n- Analyze user behavior metrics\n- Gather feedback through surveys\n- Use heatmaps and interaction tracking\n\n5. Industry Standard Guidelines\n- Follow Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)\n- Adhere to Nielsen Norman Group's usability heuristics\n- Implement established design patterns\n- Learn from successful website designs\n\nThe key is balancing objective usability standards with user-specific needs through continuous testing and iteration.",
